Disease outbreaks reported
---------------------------------------
While every effort is made to present verified information on these pages,
in the early stages of outbreaks, the picture may be unclear. In such
instances we will clearly indicate that the information is not yet fully
verified. Such basic information as the nature of the clinical illness, the
number and location of cases, and confirmation of the diagnosis may likewise
be unavailable. Reports from different sources may give
conflicting data. Through contact with national health authorities, we
intend to provide timely and accurate information about major events and
offer prompt updates as the picture unfolds.
22 July 1999
Unknown illness in the Russian Federation
------------------------------------------
On 1 July 1999, WHO was notified that the Ivanovsky Institute of Virology
had confirmed 4 cases of Crimean-Congo haemorrhagic fever ( see the WHO fact
sheet on CCHF) in the Stavropol region between the Black sea and the Caspian
sea. Of the 4 cases, 2 were fatal. The Ministry of Health reported the
situation to be under control.
On 17 July [1999, cases of an unknown disease were reported by the press in
the
village of Oblivskaia, north of Stavropol, in the region between Volgograd
and Rostov-on Don, many of them among children. The first case was reported
to have occurred on 5 July, and up to 8 deaths have been associated with
this illness. Eighty-one patients are said to have been admitted to hospital
in the region. On 19 July [1999, press reports also mentioned 32 similar
cases in the Volgograd city area, including 1
adolescent originating from Oblivskaia. Press reports have suggested a link
between the unknown illness and the 4 CCHF cases confirmed at the beginning
of July in Stavropol, but at the moment there is inadequate clinical or
epidemiological information to support any link.
The WHO Regional Office for Europe is in contact with the local health
authorities for verification of these events.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@usa.healthnet.org>
[Notice the disclaimer at the beginning of this report. This is from the
WHO CSR web page. It's interesting that there are reports based on the
newswires pre: confirmation with local health authorities. Usually WHO
waits for confirmation from the formal health sector before issuing an
alert - MPP
[*****This is a very welcome development. For too long, reporting of new
outbreaks by WHO has been delayed by having to wait for official clearance -
Mod.JW
