[3
Date: Fri, 23 Jul 1999 16:30:22 -0400
From: rbl@hal.EPBI.CWRU.Edu (Robin B. Lake)

The following comment came in reply to a ProMED-mail message I forwarded to
a colleague who is living in Stavropol:
"First, yes, there is an epidemic of CCHF in Rostov/Stavropol regions. It
occurred first in Rostov region and has seeped into Stavropol and another
region. It is tentatively identified as CCHF. The actual identification will
be next week (I don't know why it takes so long).
When we got back from the Black Sea (week of vacation) on 17 Jul 1999 the TV
was covering the crisis. Margaret (my wife) was extremely concerned as it
was reported to be carried by ticks in stage 1 and to be aerosol (multiple
doctors caught the virus). I cannot tell you when it was first reported
except to say we heard nothing on 8 Jul 1999 when we left.
I looked everywhere on MSNBC web site (my only regular news source) and
found nothing. Glad to hear that the outside public hears something."
--
Robin Lake
Environmental Modeling Inc.
and Dept. of Epidemiology and Biostatistics, CWRU
rbl@po.cwru.edu
[*****First, we highly commend this sort of initiative by our subscribers.
If you know of a friend or colleague living in the area of a reported new
outbreak, please pass our reports on to them with a request for an
update.*********
Second, reports say that 2 of the 3 doctors who became infected are now out
of danger. Hospital staff are much more exposed to ´aerosol´ transmission
than the general public, since they have to peer into patients´ body
cavities, mop up their blood & excrement, give them injections & perform
cut-downs to put in needles for transfusions.
Third, there still seems to be a belief on the spot that the Stavropol
epidemic is an extension of the Rostov CCHF outbreak rather than a separate
episode with a different cause. We shall see - Mod.JW
